The "excessive taxation" thing was just my opinion, in fact I said as much. And when I talked about the Nordic countries being closer to free markets I meant less regulations over all, I believe they are at the top of the Economic Freedom Index.
For the market to work, companies have to fail and we should let them fail, obviously. If we don't, society's limited resources are used less effectively and to causes consumers desire less, that is a recipe for disaster.
I won't get into banks because it's pretty long, but just so you know, banks should fail and they will always fail. The practice of loaning deposits inherently creates cycles of boom and bust, that is basically what every bank does today. Today we have fractional reserve banks, I believe we should have full reserve banks, they don't create money out of thin air to loan out. If you don't know what I'm talking about, I suggest you look into the Austrian Business Cycle and how banks and governments increase the money supply.
Going back to what we were talking about, I just think states should stay out of it. I think the market comes up with better solutions, not only to the climate problem, but to pretty much everything.
I don't think the "overly insane hunger for profit" is a bad thing, in fact the profit motive (or how Adam Smith called it "the desire for betterment") is essential to human action and the market. It is what makes it work. I know most people when they call it "excessive" they are concerned for workers, I suppose that's at least part of what you mean. If the contract between an employer and his employee is voluntary, as it is and should always be, the employee doesn't need to accept it, he can look for a higher paying job. Also, the role of unions is essential to pushing wages up until their actual market value, the problem is today they try to push it higher through government action. Going back to competition, employers also compete between themselves to get employees, which pushes salaries up.

To sum up, I don't think we'll agree, we just have different world views. I don't like the state, I think most of their policies, although they may have good intentions, have bad results. We should agree to disagree, I guess :D

1. The point wasn't to get China, India and Pakistan below a 2% increase. Even if that was the case it didn't succeed in doing that, if no one enforces it and they can decide their goals, they won't do anything. And they haven't done anything.

2. The US pollutes far less than China today and, in fact, America is one of the fastest countries in reducing carbon emissions. This reduction is not thanks to any government regulation or subsidy, it is because of natural gas, fracking and nuclear power. You may not like them, but they produce by far more energy and more efficiently than wind and solar (actually solar energy panels have to be replaced every 5 years and pollute more because of this). With time, maybe solar or wind energy could become more efficient, but the fact remains that if the government subsidizes them, they won't develop as fast (If you give money to a company to solve a problem, when the problem is solved they won't get payed anymore. @John Ver While I haven't heard of that mechanism of warming, I've heard of a very similar effect.  I'm guessing that the study was referring to the effect of particulates on warming.  Soot, sulphur dioxide, are often emitted with greenhouse gases, but they block out sunlight and reduce warming.  Water vapor clouds actually have a warming effect.

Also, when people say "x percentage of scientists agree", it's a fraught subject.  I think that if most experts agree on one thing it is significant, but what matters much more is what the literature says.  There is a consensus within climate literature as to the mechanism behind climate change.
As for what's "to blame" for the warming, that's a pretty easy one to answer.
1. We know CO2 is a greenhouse gas (absorbs IR radiation, very easy to test on your own)
2. We have many methods to measure past environmental conditions like temperature and gas concentration. This lets us determine the speed and magnitude of modern change.
3. Greenhouse gases are a vital component of climate stability.  Without them, Earth can't retain energy, and we'd be an iceball; nitrogen and oxygen do not have a greenhouse effect.  Too much of them, and we'd end up like Venus.
4. We can tell WHERE this new influx of carbon has come from.  Geological carbon is not exposed to radiation, and lacks carbon isotopes -13 and -14.  The ratio of carbon isotopes in the air has decreased in conjunction with the use of fossil fuels, while geological activity has not changed enough to be the culprit.

I've been working with the climate negotiations since the COP21 in Paris. Since John is a faithful supporter of Trump, it's of course not surprising that he provides a shallow, false view of the Paris Agreement.

Measuring the positive impacts of the Paris Agreement is too complex for this channel. It is by now a central document for international climate governance, and is integrated in many multilateral processes. It is true that the initial pledges were not at all in line with the temperature goals - but those pledges were just that, initial. What John did not include is the ratchet mechanism central to the Paris Agreement, where the pledges must be enhanced every five years - the next deadline being the end of this year, 2020. The covid-19 crisis will obviously have an impact, unfortunately a negative one probably, but we would still likely see some increase in ambition.

That being said, of course, the agreement should ideally have been much stronger, containing binding targets for example. That is however not possible in an international political system in which there is no government, and where compromises have to be made. Binding targets would not have been agreed by many countries - including the US. 

The US pulling out of the agreement was indeed a very bad decision for the climate. 

To conclude, I of course hope that Americans understand the long-term implications of climate change, also for their own country and economy, and prioritize that in their voting in November. The United States is such a great country, with so much innovation and political power. Speaking from an EU perspective, we long for the day where we can once again be allies, so that together we can push emerging economies like China towards true climate action instead of being locked in to fossil fuels.

I've been working with the climate negotiations since the COP21 in Paris. Since John is a faithful supporter of Trump, it's of course not surprising that he provides a shallow, false view of the Paris Agreement.

Measuring the positive impacts of the Paris Agreement is too complex for this channel. It is by now a central document for international climate governance, and is integrated in many multilateral processes. It is true that the initial pledges were not at all in line with the temperature goals - but those pledges were just that, initial. What John did not include is the ratchet mechanism central to the Paris Agreement, where the pledges must be enhanced every five years - the next deadline being the end of this year, 2020. The covid-19 crisis will obviously have an impact, unfortunately a negative one probably, but we would still likely see some increase in ambition.

That being said, of course, the agreement should ideally have been much stronger, containing binding targets for example. That is however not possible in an international political system in which there is no government, and where compromises have to be made. Binding targets would not have been agreed by many countries - including the US. 

The US pulling out of the agreement was indeed a very bad decision for the climate. 

To conclude, I of course hope that Americans understand the long-term implications of climate change, also for their own country and economy, and prioritize that in their voting in November. The United States is such a great country, with so much innovation and political power. Speaking from an EU perspective, we long for the day where we can once again be allies, so that together we can push emerging economies like China towards true climate action instead of being locked in to fossil fuels.

I've been working with the climate negotiations since the COP21 in Paris. Since John is a faithful supporter of Trump, it's of course not surprising that he provides a shallow, false view of the Paris Agreement.

Measuring the positive impacts of the Paris Agreement is too complex for this channel. It is by now a central document for international climate governance, and is integrated in many multilateral processes. It is true that the initial pledges were not at all in line with the temperature goals - but those pledges were just that, initial. What John did not include is the ratchet mechanism central to the Paris Agreement, where the pledges must be enhanced every five years - the next deadline being the end of this year, 2020. The covid-19 crisis will obviously have an impact, unfortunately a negative one probably, but we would still likely see some increase in ambition.

That being said, of course, the agreement should ideally have been much stronger, containing binding targets for example. That is however not possible in an international political system in which there is no government, and where compromises have to be made. Binding targets would not have been agreed by many countries - including the US. 

The US pulling out of the agreement was indeed a very bad decision for the climate.

One key problem with emissions control systems it hurts efficiency in a big way by reducing amount of oxygen a gasoline or diesel engine has to work with the PCV valve introduces oil and water vapor into the intake system and the EGR introduces carbon deposits like soot and co2 and other particulates also into the air intake system and that leads to carbon build up in the intake system from filter to the valves in intake ports on the head of the engine and as for the catalytic converters/DPF it hurts exhaust flow and also causes excessive heat buildup in the exhaust flow witch causes the engine to run hotter and all this combined hurts efficiency and performance of the engine if you were to build a engine without emission control systems the MPG would be 25 to 40 percent higher than the engines we currently have depending on the fuel used Diesel engines would have better fuel mileage than gasoline because of how they work for example the new Chevrolet Silverado 1500 with the 3.0L Duramax I6 Diesel engine and a 10 speed automatic transmission with emissions control systems gets 33 mpg but without emissions control systems it could be closer to 40 to 43 MPG and that amount of increase in mpg is a big deal because less fuel burned is a good thing.

The UN Admits That The Paris Climate Deal Was A Fraud

The day Obama threw America‚Äôs economy under the bus.
Global Hot Air: Here‚Äôs a United Nations climate report that environmentalists probably don‚Äôt want anybody to read. It says that even if every country abides by the grand promises they made last year in Paris to reduce greenhouse gases, the planet would still be ‚Äúdoomed.‚Äù

When President Obama hitched America to the Paris Accord in 2016, he declared that it was ‚Äúthe moment that we finally decided to save our planet.‚Äù And when Trump pulled out of the deal this year, he was berated by legions of environmentalists for killing it.

But it turns out that the Paris accord was little more than a sham that will do nothing to ‚Äúsave the planet.‚Äù

According to the latest annual UN report on the ‚Äúemissions gap,‚Äù the Paris agreement will provide only a third of the cuts in greenhouse gas that environmentalists claim is needed to prevent catastrophic warming. If every country involved in those accords abides by their pledges between now and 2030 ‚Äî which is a dubious proposition ‚Äî temperatures will still rise by 3 degrees C by 2100. The goal of the Paris agreement was to keep the global temperature increase to under 2 degrees.

Eric Solheim, head of the U.N. Environment Program, which produces the annual report, said this week that ‚ÄúOne year after the Paris Agreement entered into force, we still find ourselves in a situation where we are not doing nearly enough to save hundreds of millions of people from a miserable future. Governments, the private sector and civil society must bridge this catastrophic climate gap.‚Äù

The report says unless global greenhouse gas emissions peak before 2020, the CO2 levels will be way above the goal set for 2030, which, it goes on, will make it ‚Äúextremely unlikely that the goal of holding global warming to well below 2 degrees C can still be reached.‚Äù

Not to worry. The UN claims that closing this gap will be easy enough if nations set their collective minds to it.

But this is a fantasy. The list of what would need to be done by 2020 ‚Äî a little over two years from now ‚Äî includes: Boosting renewable energy‚Äôs share to 30%. Pushing electric cars to 15% of new car sales, up from less than 1% today. Doubling mass transit use. Cutting air travel CO2 emissions by 20%. And coming up with $1 trillion for ‚Äúclimate action.‚Äù

Oh, and coal-fired power plants would have to be phased out worldwide, starting now.

According to the report, ‚Äúphasing out coal consumption ‚Ä¶ is an indispensable condition for achieving international climate change targets.‚Äù That means putting a halt to any new coal plants while starting to phase out the ones currently in use.

Good luck with that. There are currently 273 gigawatts of coal capacity under construction around the world, and another 570 gigawatts in the pipeline, the UN says. That would represent a 42% increase in global energy production from coal. Does anyone really think developing countries who need coal as a cheap source of fuel to grow their economies will suddenly call it quits?

So, does this mean the planet is doomed? Hardly. As we have noted in this space many times, all those forecasts of global catastrophe are based on computer models that have been unreliable predictors of warming. And all of the horror stories assume the worst.

What the report does make clear, however, is that all the posturing by government leaders in Paris was just that. Posturing. None of these countries intended to take the drastic and economically catastrophic steps environmentalist claim are needed to prevent a climate change doomsday.  As such, Trump was right to stop pretending.

Sad, but this is a total sham. John Stossel and the ultra-conservative Manhattan Institute misrepresent pretty much everything here. It isn't the case that China just stated that it would do what it already plans to do. In fact, it stated that it would aim to reduce CO2 BEFORE 2030, and 2030 at the latest, which given growth and energy consumption projections, is actually a huge REDUCTION of the long term trend. But that's just the beginning. China also pledged to source 20% of its energy from low-carbon sources by 2030 and to cut emissions per unit of GDP by 60-65% of 2005 levels by 2030, potentially putting it on course to peak by 2027. The EU pledged a whopping 40% reduction by 2030. India pledged A 33-35% reduction in emissions intensity by 2030, compared to 2005 levels. Also pledges to achieve 40% of cumulative electricity installed capacity from non-fossil fuel based resources by 2030. Will also increase tree cover, creating an additional carbon sink of 2.5 to 3 billion tonnes of CO2 equivalent by 2030. India intends to cover the $2.5 trillion cost of its pledge with both domestic and international funds. The carbon sink and shift to sustainable energy production is huge because it reduces carbon output while allowing increased energy usage in the future; a trend that we must have if we are to succeed in reducing CO2. Brazil, critically agreed to A 37% reduction in emissions by 2025, compared to 2005 levels, with a further indicative target of a 43% reduction in emissions by 2030. Sudan, which is one of the poorest countries on earth, and uses 5% of the energy that the US does per capita (or to put it another way, Americans use twenty times more energy than Sudanese) has actually agreed to To reach 20% renewable share in the power mix by 2030. Includes detailed per-technology aims and targets for energy efficiency. Aims to raise forest area to 25% of Sudan by 2030, which, for a desert/arid and war-torn country is remarkable. And this doesn't even include all the rest of the countries or the very detailed plan for assistance, oversight and technological innovation, research, cooperation, etc... this is by far the best agreement the world has EVER SEEN. And what did the United States pledge? A 26-28% domestic reduction in greenhouse gases by 2025 compared to 2005, making its best effort to reach the 28% target, which is hardly the most difficult reduction given what other countries have committed to doing. If you were paying the slightest amount of attention you would have heard Stossel state that the planet IS warming, AND that part of the increase is likely MAN MADE.  He only criticized the stupidity and ineffectiveness of the Paris accord.  800,000 years of Antarctic ice core data confirms we are in a exceptional period of rapidly rising global temperatures.  Yes, cycles of warming followed by ice ages are normal.  However, about 97% of climate scientists believe that the use of carbon based fuels are a significant contributor to present cycle of global warming.  They DO NOT claim it is the ONLY reason.  Methane and other greenhouse gases, natural volcanic activity, as well as solar activity and the earth's orbit are also probably contributing.  The degree to which man made activity is responsible for global warming is still NOT clearly understood.  We DO know that the planet is warming even faster than the models predicted 20 years ago.  There is also significant evidence that oil and coal reserves may NOT outlast this century.  Therefore, it is critical that we now begin to transition to other energy sources like nuclear, solar, bio, etc.

I agree with Stossel on many things, so I went and read the Paris commitments. I encourage anyone here to do the same before replying.
This video is a classic case of quote mining and misquotes. All of the info below is directly from the documents submitted by the countries concerned.

China's first commitment (of four) is the peak emissions thing mentioned. The second one is "To lower carbon dioxide emissions per unit of GDP by 60% to 65% from the 2005 level" (this quote is in a list of things to do by 2030). That's a pretty concrete commitment.

Stossel misquoted India's third commitment (of eight) by adding a full stop at the end of the word intensity.
"To reduce the emissions intensity."
vs
"To reduce the emissions intensity of its GDP by 33 to 35 percent by 2030 from 2005 level."
It's clear that he is quoting this sentence (and that he therefore read the rest), as the sentence on its own would be "To reduce emissions intensity". Very dishonest quoting.
Incidentally, India's fourth commitment is "To achieve about 40 percent cumulative electric power installed capacity from non fossil fuel based energy resources by 2030." Again, a very concrete commitment.

The US, had only 1 commitment.
"achieve an economy-wide target of reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 26%-28% below its 2005 level in 2025"
If you read the literal wording of it it says "in 2025", no emissions reduction is required until the year 2025, or after it. The US was literally only committed to having slightly lower emissions for 1 year.

So let's not pretend this was a bad deal for the US in particular. The two examples of countries who got better deals very clearly had similar commitments.

Stossel also says "Of course it's true that the United States produces twice as much greenhouse gas per person as China and India"
2.35x for China. 9.82x for India. (Source: International Energy Agency)
So, while this figure is honest enough for China (allowing a bit of journalistic exaggeration), it is nowhere near being true for India. 9 times as much per capita is nothing like "twice as much".

This was a deal leaning heavily in favour of the US when looked at from this angle. If this were really about fairness in emissions (let's not kid ourselves) Trump would be proposing the same level of emissions per person i.e. China levelling off, India being allowed to increase emissions by 417% and a 63% reduction for the US. That would be fair (assuming we didn't want to count past emissions).

Before I get straw-manned, I don't think India increasing by 417%, or the US decreasing by 63% is a good idea. Let's just set a price on the global resource of clean air and let the market decide what's fair.

Undoubtedly this comment will bring all kinds of people wanting to take the argument in different directions. I'm happy to go in these directions. But first let's agree on two things. 
Was this video an honest portrayal of China and India's commitment?
Was the actual deal (not the one presented in this video) unfair?

I've been working with the climate negotiations since the COP21 in Paris. Since John is a faithful supporter of Trump, it's of course not surprising that he provides a shallow, false view of the Paris Agreement.

Measuring the positive impacts of the Paris Agreement is too complex for this channel. It is by now a central document for international climate governance, and is integrated in many multilateral processes. It is true that the initial pledges were not at all in line with the temperature goals - but those pledges were just that, initial. What John did not include is the ratchet mechanism central to the Paris Agreement, where the pledges must be enhanced every five years - the next deadline being the end of this year, 2020. The covid-19 crisis will obviously have an impact, unfortunately a negative one probably, but we would still likely see some increase in ambition.

That being said, of course, the agreement should ideally have been much stronger, containing binding targets for example. That is however not possible in an international political system in which there is no government, and where compromises have to be made. Binding targets would not have been agreed by many countries - including the US. 

The US pulling out of the agreement was indeed a very bad decision for the climate. 

To conclude, I of course hope that Americans understand the long-term implications of climate change, also for their own country and economy, and prioritize that in their voting in November. The United States is such a great country, with so much innovation and political power. Speaking from an EU perspective, we long for the day where we can once again be allies, so that together we can push emerging economies like China towards true climate action instead of being locked in to fossil fuels.
